\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid14100231 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Could you tell me the year that you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 1899. Queen Victoria, and I rem
ember her dying. Yes. Well I remember mum and - mum really crying. Come in and said - you know, I was only a tiddler, about three, and - the Queen's dead. Tears were rolling down. I still remember that. Yes. I probably was about three. Well I was only - I
 was only a little - I was alone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You were an only child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. No, I was alone at that time, that time, no, I was - she had a baby - evidently she had them regular every two years - actually, I - I did tell you that I was the oldest eleven but I'm
 not, I'm the oldest of fifteen, she lost four. Yes. Oh dear, and my poor mother. She - but - but we really - you know - enjoyed ourselves. We were - a team, you know what I mean. As the new babies came along, like - the one that was downstairs goes upsta
irs into whichever room it w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2975009\charrsid3306671 as, the boys or the girls. And}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 it was fun. And we never minded. That was the funny part - I - I've thought of it since, my goodness. But - we never minded, we - it was a family. We were together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 How many girls were there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Alive, there's - oh she - we did have - there's one more boy. We are six - six boys and five girls now. So that she had - eight boys and seven girls. Twins she had, I remember these little twins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What was the difference between your age and the youngest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
My - my youngest sister, she's in Nairobi, and I mind her children, they're at Ipswich school, one at Felixstowe and two at Ipswich, and they come to me for half term. Mabel is - she was married a year before me - she was born a year before me - I was -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 A year before you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Year - oh yes, a year before I was married, 1928.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That was when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Twenty - I think it was '28. '28. So Mabel was born '27. How old is she? I've forgotten. I can't work it ou
t. But that's it. Mabel was a baby when I had my Terry.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So the family is very spread out isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. But - the surprising part is how united we all are. We were - self sufficient put it like that, that's all I can say. I've wanted to - to fi
nd a photo of us. Yes, I wanted to find it but I've been so busy, I've been sewing you can tell and - I've been so busy that - I haven't had time to go around - to look for it. Must be up in the attic somewhere. I've brought - I've brought my whole house 
full. Anyway, you tell me what questions you want answered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I was born - oh, I was born in hospital but - my - my mother's home was at Jamaica Road, Bermondsey. Jamaica Road. Right near the river. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 How many years did you live in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
In those rooms, don't forget, in those days you just had rooms, they were flats, like a flat. 55 Russell Scott Buildings, Cherry Garden Street, Jamaica Road. I know it. Oh it was good, but - and then we moved to a little hous
e in Southwark Park Road. Then my mother had to machine - as me - history repeating itself, with work. A dozen shirts - working men\rquote 
s shirts, she used to say - hurry up home from school Lou, because I want you to help me cut out. I was eight. Cut out the s
hirts and of course I cut them wrong and she said, oh Lou. You know. But she didn't grumble. Never mind, I'll do it this afternoon. But she said, hurry home from school. Half past four I'd get home, 'cos times were different then to what they are now, hal
f past four I'd get home and all be ready on the - push chair, and I'd have to take them down to the factory. Two and nine for twelve shirts. Yes. But it - but it fed us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have to walk far to the factory then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, it was - past my school - twenty minutes walk. I pushed this thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Pushed them in a pram?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, pushed them - yes, well twelve shirts, working men\rquote s shirts. Well I was only a little girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did they keep you waiting then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, I used to go into this factory, th
is old man, it was a shop as well, go right through to the back. Come home with my two and nine. Oh mum would say, oh that's good, that'll keep us for two days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would you pick up some more work to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh yes. Yes. Bring them back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did they sometimes have no work that they wanted done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No, I - I've forgotten that, I came - used to come with a - a bundle of work on - I don't know - she might have taken a - a double - two days over them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Was it a place that was also a factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. It - it was a workroom behind the shop, and I used to have to go through the shop, up the stairs, and wait while he sorted out every little seam. Oh it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 To see whether it was good enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. Searched.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What happened if it wasn't good enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh we never - I never had any back. From mum. Yes. Yes, but I suppose they would have done but I - I - I don't think I ever brought anything back but I can't remember that. I was only - young. Yes, I was only young. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Why did she have to take the work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Well - dad was - now what was he? Oh, carman. Left home - left home at half past five in the morning, walked it to Upper Thames Street from Jamaica Road. Walk - walk early in the morning, 'cos there was only horse t
rams then, and - he would walk it to Upper Thames Street for his job and he would be out on the van. And I was the only one then, I used - he used to call in perhaps, if he was going out to the country at Chislehurst, which is - is London now - but it was
 
in the country then - and he'd call in for mum and I, little tiddler, not five 'cos I wasn't at school, and we'd be in this van, go out to the country and he would go through water, oh and I was scared stiff, you know, fords evidently over the country lan
es. But - oh I was scared of the - since I've been older, married, I told them how frightened I was of lots of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Why were you so frightened of the water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I don't know. Probably from that. Probably from that. Because - I used to wake up with
 nightmares. Right - I - I have done 'til I - 'til just before I came here. But - the answer there was that he used to take me Sunday mornings - walk over Tower Bridge and down to - Upper Thames Street, but I was - that frightened me with water, he used t
o
 say, put one foot each side, and it would wobble, you know. The bridge. Yes, where the arms come up, and he used - and he was so pleased to take me. Right Well then - we'd get to the stables, and he'd get to the stables and he'd hit one horse on its bott
o
m, and another and go all - he way down. Oh I was frightened. Of course he didn't think of me trying to hide but - a little tiddler looking up at these blooming great horses, I think that is - was my night - well - I can't tell you what me nightmares were
, but there's always this racing of a big - black thing. Yes. And I traced it now and I don't get it. Now I - understand what it was - the fear. I told 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So he was a carman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He was a carman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Who did he work for then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 It was an - an iron merchants. O'Brien Thomas. I know the name still.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And he was delivering their goods?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
He used to deliver their goods during the week. And then the weekends - Sundays and all - no, only Sundays. Saturday of course they worked - used to get h
ome ten o'clock at night, give mum a pound, don't matter how many children, a pound on the mantelpiece to keep the lot of us, of course - it's the same with me. Isn't it strange how history repeats itself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You mean that he would always give her the same amount?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did he always earn the same amount do you think or did they get overtime sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no. No. No overtime, no holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That was all his wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That was his wage - I don't know what he got, but it wasn't much. B
ut was always this pound - not given to her. Put on the mantelpiece. Which - well I - refused to accept my husband unless it gave it to me on the table. Yes, I - that is a fact. But I'm - I'm really happy - at me memories of my family. You should hear us 
when they get here. Nine of them. When I first moved in - all from South London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That's why you have such a large house then, so you can have all the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, they didn't stay, but I mean they came - one weekend. Oh it was fun. Well it is fun 
with quite a lot. Yes, yes. And - the old in-laws were just the same. Surprising - I've got one sister who doesn't get on with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 in-laws,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  she's very go she's always on the phone to me. And - she sends me some money now and again. A - a pound note in an e
nvelope. But - she is very, very good but she - she won't go and visit the in-laws at South London. You haven't asked me any questions.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said your father had to work at the weekend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well he had to go to the stables. The horses had to be fed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He was looking after the horses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Was he the sort of head horseman then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no, he had to be out on a van as a carman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But at the weekend the horseman was away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Horses - I - I couldn't tell you that, I know he used to 
take me Sunday mornings with him, to feed these horses and see to them, on Sundays. He was - yes - he was - I mean he didn't drink, didn't smoke. No, no. He was a very good father except very, very Victorian. Oh my goodness. Very Victorian. He - and I mea
n
 - my mother couldn't be in the bedroom with him, he wouldn't change his vest of anything with mother there, he says, Mouldy get out. 'Cos we all had nicknames. Oh horrible nicknames. If you heard my mother's. And mine. I could show you the postcard he se
nt from France when he was in the Army, sent through the post, dear Dusty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Why did they call you that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I don't know. I don't know, I always got the - we all had it. We always had - yes, my mother was Mouldy. It didn't matter who was there. M
ouldy, he would say, another cup of tea Mouldy. Oh - she'd say - so you don't call - she had such a nice name. Her Christian name was Kate but she was Kitty - Kit indoors and her surname's Joy. I - I think it was so pretty. I never had a daughter or else 
I
'd have named her Joy. Kitty Joy was her - before she married. But - oh I had a - a brother, he was Rasher. Still call him Rasher - right 'til dad died. Rasher. He was thin. Very thin. Always Rasher. Yes. Oh yes, Rasher. Me was Dusty. Another sister - she
 
boiled an egg, she boiled an egg, she said, oh I can't eat that it's stiff. So of course she was always stiffy after that. Another one was the Mangler, because - we're doing the - you know the old fashioned mangles, you remember with the - wood at the bac
k
. Well anyway the cat was asleep on there, Kit was mangling this sheet, then she came back with it, come backwards, the cat's tail was in it. The cat had two inches of bald - we laughed. We laughed. We - when we come over here - when they come here we lau
g
h and laugh about - but of course all my tales, we had fun over - but the others have got their tales from when I married, you see, and left them behind. 'Cos I was the first to marry. Or was I? No. I think my next brother was the first to marry. I was th
e
 first to have - first grandchild. But - oh I must tell you this, this was funny. The - we used to - my next brother, he joined the Reuters with the pillbox hat. That was in the war, dad was away in the Army. Mum said, let's come on - come up and meet Cha
r
lie. So right, we went up and met him at London Bridge, walking, he comes over the bridge with his pillbox - oh, she said, you do look nice, she said, did you get your money? She's waiting for her five shillings. Yes - yes, I got it but I've lost it. My p
o
or mother. She'd walked such a way - it's surprising how in those days, all these odd shillings they were waiting for. I earnt four shillings a week when I went to work. And I used to have threepence a week pocket money. Then bought me gloves and me bows 
out of it. Oh - poor mum. Anyway, the next brother started work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 This is alls in the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No, this was after the war with Fred. Anyway - mum takes Fred - it was an Army and Navy factory along Jamaica Road, Tooley Street. They used to do the gold
 braid on the - hats in those days. Well anyway they wanted an office boy. So mum took - I didn't go, I was at work myself, my mum took Fred along for this job, so they're sitting - this great fat man at his desk and he said, yes, he sounds very good. Wha
t
 games do you play? So poor Fred said, cops and robbers. If only he'd said football or rugger or cricket. Can you imagine it? We were - actually I think we were all - undersized. We were all brainy. We were - they were all brainy, the whole lot. Yes, the 
g
randchildren - all the grandchildren are all grammar school, university a lot of them, and - my two were grammar school. The others all have been. But - there was something - not - was it because we never had milk. Because we never had cows milk, was alwa
ys tinned milk. Then when the war came that was stopped, I went without a drink for months - because I couldn't - well I couldn't drink anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Children were smaller then weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, we were all tiny. You wouldn't think you could go out 
to work. But we did. And I always remember Charlie, little Charlie - little tiny Charlie, great big pillbox.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 How long did your father have this job as a carter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh - he kept that - he kept that 'til he nearly retired. And then he went - my broth
er - my second brother - did - shirts, mother was you know, a shirtmaker and when I was tiny and she always did it you see and - and any other odd sewing. But it was in the family that Ben went to a shirt place. And he is a manager of - a big place in Pic
cadilly. He - he measures up all the Royals - the heads of the Royal Family. Yes, Prince Bernard and all those. Yes, it's - we're all - you see - talking about me and us older ones, it was all work to keep - to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 get}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  the money for food. Yes. See, and mum used
 to say, well now look it's - dad's in bed. I can't machine now. Go on, you go to bed. And then she used to do the work then, housework and cooking. After - ten - nine or ten. So that I never had any training for housework.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Because you never saw her doing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. No. No. Yes, it does reflect on your - I mean I'm always in a mess. Not that I'm caring. My family like to come. The whole lot, they all like to come. They say, oh Lou, we like to get here 'cos you don't mind if we drop a crumb, which I
 don't. The - the grandchildren play here, the - with the cotton reels. I leave them about. Well - why not, it's me own place. Why not. Of course I like - to - I have a grand slam at the weekends when my son comes. The older one. He'll be here this week.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So just before he retired he did get this other job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. He - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 oh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  yes, he went to my brother's firm as an odd job man. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 There was nothing else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. Then he - oh no, well you couldn't chop and change jobs, if you got a job you were lucky, you know, then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did he do anything before he became a carter as far as you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. I wouldn't know. They were very young when they married. I think - mum was eighteen - and dad must have been twenty. Had no parents. They all - both 
died. Oh - there was one grandfather. But mum's mother died - she - they come up from Devonshire. Yes. Yes. And lived - how they lived in - round there - but - near the Southwark Park it was they lived. Her mother lived. 'Cos she said, oh it was wonderful
. They had doves, and a donkey - I can imagine them. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 In Southwark?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, in Southwark. Number 12 Maxon Street - was where she lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Had a donkey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, she said they had - well there was ground at the back. There was ground at the 
back, I - of course it's flattened now. But - mother said - oh - in a home - but of course she died when she was about eleven I think. And it's the same with my - dad. He lived at Storts Road, Bermondsey, I've got his birth certificate and - and family, a
nd - I think his parents died early. Which they do in those days. I mean, life on the waterside then must have been dread - I don't remember it a lot. We - and us as a family, we stayed in our house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You moved to Southwark Park from Jamaica Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Southwark Park Road. When we moved there the twins - she had the twins there. Got to go back. Lou, Charlie, Kit, Ben - '99. Was two there.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Can you tell me the order of the names?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh - Lou - it's strange, she never realized, we've all got you f
or our second name. Us girls. The five girls. Mind you, I like mine best. It was May. Louise May. And we - we call one another by our two names. Louise May. Katherine Minnie. Dorothy Matilda, Gladys Mary and Ethel Mabel. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And then the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I'm just thinking when we went to Southwark Park Road. She had the twins In Southwark Park Road. Then she had another baby. But you wouldn't know there was any. There was twins born and died at fifteen months old, but we're still regular every two years. 
Strange isn't it? Well - you see Ben is January.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Can you give me the boys names?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Ah - Charles. Charles Arthur. Is it? No, Charles Edward. Arthur died. Charles Arthur died, Arthur Charles died. Charles Edward. Benjamin Alfred. Fred William. No, E
rnest. Ernest - Ernest Frank, Fred William. Albert John. James Stanley. That's right. And the twins - the prettiest little girls I ever saw, and she had the three babies all - alike. Then it - she had another one the next year which was my Babs. And - you
 
wouldn't have known the difference. The twins were so tiny and Babs was a hefty - and they were all together, and then the twins died at fifteen months. I think Babs was two months old when they died. And that's - of course we still continue at - every tw
o years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So about how old were you when the twins were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I'm sorry you - turn off a minute. I can't think. There's four - must have been eight years. I must have been - I must have been eight.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Why did they move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh, for the house. With more rooms. Rooms, we moved to a house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So that was more expensive probably?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, probably - yes. I wouldn't know, I - I've forgotten that. It was a house in Southwark Park Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Was it just about then you started taking the work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Taking the work down. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Maybe because they needed a bit more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. Yes, perhaps - that might have been the reason, she - that she needed money. Yes. I've never analysed that bit myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 How long did you live in that road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 S
outhwark Park Road - we lived - then we went to - where we was there for thirty or forty years, in Anchor Street, Bermondsey. Anchor Street, Bermondsey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So you weren't very long in Southwark Park Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, it was fair. I was there after the war
. Yes, 'til after the war. Yes, it - after the war, then we was Anchor Street. The shirts fell off and then mum went - dad was in the Army, mum went out then carriage cleaning on the railway, which the junction was quite near us. Oh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Which junction is that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 South Bermondsey station. No, South Bermondsey station. And - I think the whole things were left on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 derelict}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  ground there for cleaning, you know, it was a yard. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So she was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 a shirtmaker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  and she also did carriage cleaning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were there any other jobs that she did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. That was all. And - by that time the children were going out to work, fetching in their little bits. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 'Course we lived under the shadow then of Peak Frean's biscuits - you know, there was a great big tower and we lived - we never - looked at the clock, we used to go to the door and look at -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You had no clock in the house you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well - we knew - there must have been but - we never bothered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Some people didn't did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you remember a clock in the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No I don't. But - oh we had some casualties too. I set the house on fire once. Well I was only tiny. This was in - Southwark Park Road, so I was eightish. Oh go in the other room, front room
 you know, of course it was all draped with - these Victorian hangings over the fireplace. Go in the other room and light the gas. And of course I did, I lit the gas things and threw the match in the fireplace, turned round to lift up the shutters. Oh - t
h
e whole thing was - yes. I screamed. Poor mother. She was burnt. Yes. I know - we got over it. We laugh about it now, that is the point. Then I got a brother, this brother Fred, his - he - he was a - a devil for electric things. And - anyway he had some b
a
tteries and he's up in his bedroom and he just puts it in the - electricity, a battery thing, whatever he was doing. Oh that set the bedroom alight. I wasn't there, I was married, but of course that is one of the tales that the others laugh at. Oh dear. B
u
t - what I must say - as regards - the modern generation and the olden times, there's much more fun in the olden times, you made your own pleasure. We all did. I can't - describe it. There is that feeling of - but there wasn't the show of affection. Not t
h
at there is now. And I didn't have it. Probably - I mean we loved them all as the babies came along, we loved them and mum'd say, go in the other room and mind Jimmy, 'cos I must do this work. Right, well you would do that. And you loved them, but there w
a
sn't - the love from the mother to the child. The way you would sit and - cuddle the child all the time. I - sort of analysed that. Yes. Yes. But - but you - she still did love us all, we were all a united family. But - well - well the - the children only
 
ever played in the garden. Our younger ones, I never went out to play. I was all work. You know, I never thought of it - no, I never thought of it, that was the point. I still don't ever sit still. See, I've got all this - I - I never sit still at all. Ye
s. Never mind. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Your parents were married in about 1893 or so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So they were in their early twenties when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That's right. Yes. Mum was only nineteen. It - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 at a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  big church at St James'. St James' Road, the b
ig church. Used to be Scot - yes, Scott Lidgett was the pastor at that time, yes. Yes. Very well known, he used to speak on the radio. You wouldn't know. Big man he was. Doctor Scott Lidgett, he was - nice man. Mum's - wedding. But we were very - I wouldn
't say she - we were religious. But we always had to go to Sunday school. Yes. Yes. Yes. The tribe. Lou t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 oo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
k the tribe down. And - if we didn't eat our food it was there when we came home, with me with the greens. I hated them. The same with fat. I still do
n't like it. Probably - I wouldn't say we were forced to, 'cos mum would snaffle it out if she could, but dad would say - we were never - hit by mum. Dad did. Yes. I remember - dropping a cup, 'cos it was always washing up you know, do that kind of work, 
and - just dripped a cup on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 the scullery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 floor and - right, he came out and it was old fashioned trousers you know with a window at that back you know, button that you let it down, he let it down and - oh he did sting me. Just for breaking a cup.
