\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So you started helping right from he beginning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Right from the beginning, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Your mother never had anyone at all coming in to help her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no. No. No. But that wasn't thought of in those days, not our class. We were real just working class on the - riverside, more or less.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did she ever take in a lodger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. When we had a lodger we moved to Anchor Street. We had a lodger. The big front room upstairs. There was - a lot of room - not a lot, three bedrooms and we let this one big front room with two windows. Mr and Mrs Brown. She used to come d
ownstairs and borrow the baby. She used to say, oh Mrs Gardner, let me borrow your baby, I've only got a farthing left. So mum'd say, all right. And she used to take her farthing with the baby on her arm to go and buy a farthingworth of sweets for herself
. She didn't have the check to only ask for a farthing - one ounce you see in those days, four ounces a penny. But I can always remember Mrs Brown coming down and saying, Mrs Gardner, let me borrow your baby. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But you didn't have a lodger before that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no. No. And then when she went we didn't at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you ever have any other relatives living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Oh no. Too many of us. And - we did have fun, I must say that. We - Sundays we would have a big - scrubbed table in the
 kitchen, you know, with - we'd all fetch our claims in as well and we'd get all these boards, one from behind the mangle, more boards from outside, mum's grapevine, under the - the ledge under the grapevine and - we'd put them on two chairs, you know, so
 
that we all sat round and we'd play for hours, not - with - with mum and dad, playing with balloons. Now we made our own fun. Yes. Just - you know, we'd have tea, bread and butter of course and - there might have been watercress. There might have been wat
e
rcress. And dad had a treat once a month I think, he had winkles. Black bits all round the edge of the - oh I have a horror of those. Yes. Oh - no. I can still see dad's little black caps round the plate. Oh no - oh - I say the living was different then. 
But - she - we always had butter. But it was only tenpence a pound. But - she was a very good manager.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 How did she manage with washing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You mean Lou did it. Light the copper, you know, one of these - big coppers, light the thing and - it would b
e all boiling by the time you got home from school and then you put the copper stick in and dished them up and then let them drain and - yes, well I wouldn't say me only, we did it between us. But it was always - shared, we'll do this, we'll do that you k
now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Once a week was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, it was only bath night once a week. Friday nights, in the old tin bath in the scullery. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Clean clothes once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh yes. Is there a picture there? No, it's fallen down, I was going to show you a p
icture of my sister. Beautiful clothes, she would have a - all had pinafores, you know, pinnies and with all the frill goffered all round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 She made them herself did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes - no, I think she made them. She made them but I meant she would do thi
s frill round and - and - you know like curling irons, and she would make this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 goffer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 thing that stood out - oh horror. I - there is a picture somewhere, it's fallen down behind there. Picture of my sister in one, that was my next sister so I knew I had it just the same. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were you ever taken out to shop to buy clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Oh I still don't, everything is all my - all made. Myself. I've never had any - any bought clothes. No. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 She made the boys clothes too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I don't know, I've forgotten - I've forgotten that, but with me - I'm talking about me, I never had anything new - ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well I suppose we must have had those new, I've forgotten. That's why I've got bad feet I think, wearing her cast offs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Your father didn't repair the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. Dad }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 did}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  nothing. - Nothing at all. He never - never washed or moved a thing - off the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about decorating in the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no, mum did that. Me and mum. Me and mum. Mother - mother and I did the kitchen every year for Christmas. Yes, mother and I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would he light a fire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh yes. Yes, he kept the fire. The fire was always in, the range was mostly always in. Then of course our hot water - we'd all go up to bed, this - the oven w
as full of bricks, so we'd all have a brick rolled up in a flannel, and when you went to bed - the children went to bed they took a brick up and of course the end it was mum and I left alone so we - I had the plates and mum had the three things it stood o
n for our hot. Yes, it was, but it still answered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said that you did go out with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, dad would take me out - Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would he help any of the children in any other way, would he help them bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no, dad did nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about telling them stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, not dad. No. Mum. Mum would tell us - or she always did to me. No, dad, no. He was always work}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 ing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 . At - you know - so early in the morning and then when he was home at night he was so tired he went to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did he just take you out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That was a special privilege for the eldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I don't know why, no, of course I was the only one. Don't forget she had two boys and lost them. Yes, there's a gap. And then my - he never took any of the ot
hers out ever. Yes. And it's surprising. And - also he did when I was older. He took me - used to take me walking all the way mind you to the Coliseum. Yes. That's all variety in those days I think. But I know he took me to this great big place with the d
ome.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did he take you inside though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, oh yes, we went to the show for a shilling I think it was. Yes, he did - take me about. Oh - as far as he could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were you closer to him than the others were do you think then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, I was clo
ser to my mother. Because we were all together, mother and I always, we fed the family. We would be in the scullery and feed them, serve out - give that to so and so, the next one and the next one, all round this big table, where mum would be cutting and 
she'd say - put a bit in me mouth you know, we wouldn't any food really because we'd be having little bi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
s. I don't think we ever sat down much with them. No. 'Cos there's all the clearing up to do afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did the other children help in the home as well as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Well I used to resent it because I thought they didn't, but they must have done. I used to be mad with my next sister, 'cos she used to pinch all my cottons, you know they'd be lying upstairs for sewing in my bedroom, I used to come hom
e - when I started work - I used to come home and find she'd been at me cottons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But you don't remember them having tasks like you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, but they must have done. They must have done their share because of - Kit mangling the - mangling the cat
 you see. Yes, she must have done her share. And she must - the other one, Babs, must have done something because of her boiling the egg. But I wouldn't say they did any - work as I - was always on the go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You were almost the second mother were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, I was, yes. I was. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 
And they - they treat me as their second mother, yes, they're very, very good. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
The whole lot of them. A brother came over here - I met him in the High Street, I - I saw him at the funeral, mum's funeral, twelve years ago, oh, i
t's thirteen now, but anyway, twelve years I hadn't seen him, when I was on me bike in the High Street talking to one of the Women's Institute women, I said, oh I'm not going tonight. So then, a couple was coming along - and I thought to myself - oh she m
ust be one of the Women's Institute women, so I said, hello. So she said, it is Lou. It was my brother and sister-in-law. Had come up - come over from Woolwich and found me in the High Street. Now isn't that marvelous. Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 And he is - he is very, very good. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
He's been a - been each year since. I remind him 'cos I send them their cards - birthday cards. But I carry on where mum left off. Never forget anybody's birthday. On the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did your mother always do that for the whole family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Regular, on th
e day. We were very hurt if we didn't get it. And - I still do the same. And they say, oh - what sit - Ernie came a fortnight ago, three weeks ago, he said something about, yes, you still carry on like mum did don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you think her mother was like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Well she remembered. She - she died at eleven. You do pass it on, yes, But - Surprisingly we're all - there's - the whole gang of us you know but don't matter when you pick the phone up you know who it is. We all - the girls talk alike. Us g
irls. You pick one up and you say - oh that's Glad. And the boys too. Yes. We're -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Talking about your grandmother with this donkey, do you know what they were doing with this donkey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. Yes, I - no, they were family pets. Family pets. It
 was mother's family - her mother's family pets and she - she loved her doves and she bought the doves up. She - I think she was religious, as opposed to - well I wouldn't say we're religious. I certainly believe - but that's all, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But not that strongly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When you went to work you were still expected to carry on with these tasks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Really as long as you were at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well until I did get boyfriends. That's the point. But we had to be in - by nine too. Yes.
 There was a real row if - if we weren't in. I would go to the church dances, dances at the church, it was only over the road, the Manor Methodist and - I'd got to be in by nine. But - I mean my sons, cor, two or clock in the morning. With a racing car at
 that. Yes. Never mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about bedtime when you were at school, when would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Well, I didn't have any homework in those days. I - I was - went to a higher grade school and I felt very proud of that, of being at this higher grade school,
 but there wasn't homework. But - of course all that time I was working with mother, not working but helping her. If it wasn't doing anything with the machining it was minding the children, take them out or do something out of her way while she could - wo
rk before dad got in. And it was - oh the noise of it. 'Cos she couldn't do it when dad - it was the next room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He wouldn't let her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh well she wouldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When he'd gone to sleep she did the housework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. That's right. No, she wouldn
't do the machining while dad - 'cos it was only in the next room, because their bedroom was downstairs, it was four rooms down and four rooms up. Five rooms up I think, a little one. Anchor Street, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Was there a set time when you had to go to bed when you were at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, oh yes, take your hot water bottle up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You were last in a way weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. I was last, yes. It's surprising how we were - always together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You and your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 My - yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 
It was a very, very sad blow when - they both - dad died first, oh I thought the world had come to - we all did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
It was a real Victorian bedside drama. Can you imagine eleven of us all round the bed watching him die.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That was when?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Dad died. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 In 1954. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
And mother - and a few weeks later - with history repeating itself, she had notice to quit. 'Cos the London Country Council were clearing the slums. Right. I - that was the same with me with my husband died. My landlord, we were
 only renting, well so was mum, we were only renting then and - I just had notice to quit, that's why I came here. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh - my husband - '62. Yes. But it doesn't seem possible that history could repeat itself like that, in more t
han one thing. Oh yes. Yes, it seems to - but - anyway I miss them. Miss them very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 If you were worried about something would you talk to your mother about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about your father, would you talk to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well only wh
en he retired, he was there. But - as children never left our parents. They - well - not - not me mum and dad, we was always calling in, I had - I worked and then I used to tear up to London, take my work in and pop in to see mum and dad and then get home
 
to do my husband's dinner - lunch, 'cos he was a builder, decorator you know and I had to - have a meal ready. Well - dad died and the whole lot of the boys never left her. They called in - it was arranged - one would call in every night. But - we found o
u
t - and us girls would go up during the day. The five - the four girls at the time, Mabel was in Africa, and - we found out when she was ill, when she died, that the worst thing we could have done to her. Because she went back to buildings, Council got he
r
 a flat in - in Jamaica Road again and of course the boys called in on their way home from work, sat for an hour and saw that she was all right and then shut the door and went. And she missed her garden. Yes. And - we - we always - when we all gathered to
gether we found out that she was - it was the worst thing we could have done, but we did think we were doing the right thing, never leaving her, or calling in every night. You see, she'd always got to be there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So she could never really get on with anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. That's right. Yes. Oh tell me any more questions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What did your mother cook on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Ah - we had a gas stove, but when money was low she'd say, now look Lou, shall we have two pound of potatoes or shall we put the penny in the gas? O
h, I'll go and get two pound of potatoes. And she would cook 'em on the - the range. Yes. And - then when she'd got the money, two and - I'd take home two and nine a dozen shirts home, two an - oh, that's good, go up to Woods and get three pound of pieces
.
 And that was a - the old fashioned butcher with the chopping blocks in the middle. Have you ever seen pictures of them? You know, with the great big - well, they - that's what was in the olden days, pre first war, and - now she'd go right down to a certa
in man on one of these chopping blocks, I used to come home with a bagful of beef pieces. It would last for three or four days - for sixpence. Of course }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  was a lot in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When you say the money was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 short}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 , why would the money be short sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Well, because it was short, she hadn't - see dad's money only really paid the rent and bought the coal or something else. She'd got to earn the money to keep us more or less, yes. And to sit and do a dozen shirts with half a dozen kids - 'cos we
 were at school and our - we never had the holidays we do now, and our times were different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But he was never out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, he was never out of work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about if he was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, he was never ill. No. I've never known him be at home. No, until he was near retiring age, then he did - he was ill with }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 bronchitis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
, but - he - in our young days he was never ill. But that was as far as the money went in those days. And - of course, she'd got the opportunity to get some work done to ge
t some money, that was the point, but when money did get short she - no, what did she say to me, oh - go up to Woods or go up to - no, go up the shops this time - go up the shops and get a bloater for dad's tea, or get a kip - get a haddock. Threeha'pence
. Right. And take the child in the pushchair. And I've put it down the back of this pushchair, and I came home with the paper one day and no haddock, it had slipped out. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you eat in the room where she cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. There was a scullery. Like me. Scullery. And the living room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And you always ate in the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. In the - yes,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You never ate in the front room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, that was best. That had the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 gramophone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 This is Anchor Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Anchor Street. Yes. Yes, all right, Anchor Street. That was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 gramophone}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
. When we had the best room. No, we'd - we let - we seldom used that because the fuel. I was all - well, it was - it was - everyone used to go into the living room, same as they do here. You know, always come in here, never go into my other room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You still keep a parlour do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Well, I wouldn't say a parlour, got a divan in there but I - I think it's warmer here. And I've got to go upstairs for the bathroom. So I might as well be upstairs in the bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You feel more comfortable sleeping upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I do here, on the - on the road. 'Cos I mean ten o'clock at night this bell will ring. Yes. And it's - people going by ring the bell.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Just for fun?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. I've got a chain on now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When did you have breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 A bit of bread and butter. That's all. Yes, one bit of bread and butter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I don't know what he had. He went off - he had to be at work by six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And he didn't come home for the midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No, oh no. No. He was out all day. I don't know what happened. He was out all day. But she would get him something for his tea, which was a haddock or a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 bloater}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 , pan of kippers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have anything at midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh yes, yes, she wou
ld do a meal. It wasn't a lot but she would - a pan of herrings. She - she thought of the food value, and it was cheap then, it was tuppence a pound for the herrings and two pounds a penny potatoes and she would - we would make do with that. There wasn't 
the green stuff. We never went - never thought of it, whether it was about or not I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You never ate vegetables at all except for potatoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, I don't think so. Or she would have a stew, now what would she do with a stew? I never though
t about it, it would always be on the hob.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Put some potatoes in that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Probably. The - the stew - part of these pieces that I mentioned. Three pound of pieces - would go into stew, there would be a pie of some. Then a pudding, some. And then the rest probably would be in a saucepan on the hob cooking away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 A sort of suet pudding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, it was suet crust. Yes, suet crust.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When would you eat that, for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, midday for us. Midday. The children - children - us - I don't know what mum had I don't - nor me much, we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 feeding}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 the others or - but I - well, we were quite all right really. But - I don't remember us sitting down really to eat like that. It was always a - what I remember - it was always getting them going and - then 
you'd got to feed the baby, 'cos he'd have to have milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did the others have set places at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. Children - dad - dad had his swivel chair, nobody sat in that. And we all just went round.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you all sit down together, or sort of come in casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No, not a lot. No. But of course the children at the other - children were at the school over the road and they were home quick. I had a twenty minutes walk and - we didn't even have a meal then, we'd got to wait 'til one o'clock I 
think, because I'd have to do some cutting out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You had to do some work before you had your food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. Yes. Clear the table. Do this cutting out for mum. Then that was cleared once I'd cut these shirts out. And then get the - 'cos the table was always empty, you know, it was a scrubbed table, so that was always empty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Midday you'd have either fish or meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Fish or meat. I was a meal. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And that was your big meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That was a big meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What did you have for tea then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Just bread and butter again. Bread and butter again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But your father had his main meal in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, dad - for dad she get a - a kipper or a bloater, something in the fish line.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would he not have the meat somet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 imes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, he never had that, no. Whether he had anything out during the day or not}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 I don't know. - At that time I don't think we saw enough of dad to - to be interested. Well I - the problem didn't arise. We - we never thought so much of nutrition in those days did we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So about how many times a week do you think you would have meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Well, mostly most of the days. Something - meat or fish. If she was short of money we would share the herrings between us and the mashed potatoes. She - she did think
 of us. No, there is something about it that - as a family where you do all love one another - the years fall away and you're back as you were that - 'cos I - actually I'm the image of my mother. Just when she died. Yes, I mean in looks and everything. Wh
e
n she died I'm just the same. But you know I don't - and yet the kids - I haven't seen Bert - no, I haven't seen Ben last year for - about thirteen to fourteen - since the funeral I hadn't seen him 'til they took me up to London. Oh, he said, the old girl
 herself. She hasn't changed a scrap. But you are, 'cos he had. He's filled out. He's the image of - my uncle - Uncle Ben, and a cousin of mine.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you see much of them, the uncle, when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. We saw them once a fortnight. And -
 the other fortnight dad would walk to them, a Sunday tea. And of course - after it was all over, after dad died or after what - no, after Uncle died, I found out that my mother was always furious that he would go and leave her. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 This Sunday - Sunday afternoon him and Bill would go and see Til and Perce, and they would go, get home at midnight, dad would take his Carter's Little Liver pills because he'd been having a blow out. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, evidently they had got plenty of - more money. He was a milkman and he made h
is money on watering the milk in those days. Yes. It's true. That is - that is true. He used to work for the Co-op. You know, on one these floats with a churn. One horse and a - a - a float. And he bought some houses in Hilda Road, Canning Town, and he pa
id the firm back more than he was earning. So they sacked him. Yes. That was true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That's your father's brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. But - I mean that is true. And he used to go over to this - family at Canning Town, him and another brother, leave mum. I n
ever knew anything about it, I was too ignorant. And - but I - I realized it - that she must have been - well you would feel neglected wouldn't you, always producing infants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have special food on Sundays or home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 For us? Yes, always had 
a - a joint. Half a shoulder. No, a little one, only lasted the - just give us all a bit. Half a shoulder. But we could only go and buy that late Saturday night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well because he used to come home from the stables late see. Ten o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 With the money - you hadn't go paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. And the - in those days the markets were open 'til midnight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Who would go and buy it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Me and mum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You went out together?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Me and mum. Up the Blue. It was Blue Anchor. 
Yes, it's called the Blue Anchor Market. It's gone now I think. It's all shops. But it was a market and mum'd say, well let's come up the Blue and get the shopping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What else would you buy while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh, potatoes and eggs, two a penny. Oranges two a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So you had fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh yes. Yes. Oh-yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were the eggs for boiling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 They must have been.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Boiling or frying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, no, I don't think we had fried eggs, I think that they were boiled. Now, we didn't use the frying pan a lot. Not in those days. No. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 She was very, very good as a mother.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That was the advantage of working at home I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. That's right - it is, that - that's why I always worked at home. My children, I was never away. They came ho
me from school I was there. And with my husband - 'cos I had my husband all the time. Used to come in half past ten for his cup of tea. And it had got to be ready too. Except when I was going out, well then, I've got to go up with the work today. Well tha
t's all right. He - all right, I can do me own tea, me lunch. But I'd got to have his meal there. One o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Who looked after the cooking, was it your mother, or did you do quite a bit of the actual cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Me mother. Me mother. And of course a lot of it was on the hob, in the oven. 'Cos the - the - this kind of range was always alight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 How did she do the potatoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh they were boiled on the hob. Yes. In one of the black iron saucepans. About as big as that. I always remember that. A
nd we had oxtail once. I remember that. And the bones were all collected on our - you know - we take the bones out, they were put back in the saucepan and redone, and it was thick jelly. No meat with them but there must have been a bit of goodness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did she make any soup then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That's right. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 
She was - she was very, very good in her reasoning about feeding us. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I will always give her her due for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would you have a soup as well as a meat dish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no. No. No. That would be the next. The
y would be on the hob for the next day. 'Course put barley in and all this that and the other. Yes. Probably we'd have toast on it, you know, toast it in front of the fire and these little squares of toast put in. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 She - she was very, very good in her reasoning of feeding us You know.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did she bake her own bread ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would she make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. That's special treat for Sunday. We used to go over and buy a ha'porth. Take our - 'cos it used to be sold in big jars then. And we used to take a little stone jar and go and buy a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 
hap'orth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  of jam for Sundays tea. Oh poor mum. But we didn't know any different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did she make any pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. She - she did nothing but make wine from her grapevine. That's the only cooking - preserves I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Which house was that though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh, Anchor Street. Anchor Street she did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 She wouldn't make wine before that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no. No. Only had the long garden at the front in Southwark Park Road. No, she was very proud of the lawn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 She didn't do any bottling or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, nothing. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did she make medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. No. Not at all, I think we were fairly healthy, more or less. I don't remember us - having medicines. Not much. Oh yes, I must have done, I've had - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  and scarlet fever. I've been away to hospital. When I was little. Five at Shooters Hill, yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 Diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 . That's scarlet fever. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 Diphtheria when I was older.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you remember going to the hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. I do remember going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did they come and visit you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I've forgotten. I don't suppose they did. They couldn't go from Jamaica Road to Shooters Hill. In any case it was isolation hospital in those days. Yes, in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 They took it very seriously then didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes
 they did. That - that was me, but I don't remember any of the others. They might have done after I left, because she had - the last child after I left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You don't remember being visited by a doctor at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. Only for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Or being sent to the dispensary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. Only for her when she had children. Although - only the last couple we had to have the doctor home. Mainly that was the woman round the corner delivered them. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 A neighbour you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Go round and get Mrs C
ollins. Yes. Yes. Yes, I'm - I'm surprised now that she had so many of us, and we're all healthy. Yes. Well I consider we're healthy, I don't think I'm bad. I still ride me bike. At seventy-two. Yes. No, I'm - I'm very veiny, I suppose you can't expect an
ything else. No, but that is - we must have been healthy. I think she did look after us in - as far as she could with the food. Yes, and she was a marvelous woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did she buy any tinned food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Not even corned beef?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. T
here wasn't he - we never had it. It was always sold in long tins if you did want it. No, we - no - we didn't have that. All - when I started work - no, not with me, it was Kit, Kit went to Peak Freans and she used to bring home three pound of biscuit cru
m
bs. They were for sixpence. Yes. In a bag like that we had a - we had a treat, not me, but the kids - the kids, they - I still call them the kids - the kids, stay in bed Saturday morning with a bag of biscuit crumbs. Yes. But - they - I - we never had any
 luxuries, just bread and butter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you ever eat bananas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You did mention the watercress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 We had - yes, that's for Sunday tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You all had watercress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well it was on the table. For Sunday tea that was our treat. B
read and butter was cut, big plateful and we had what we wanted, and the watercress was our treat, and dad with his winkles. Oh I don't know what poor mum had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He never had jellied eels?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh gawd no. Oh I was old at this time, I was at work when 
she said, let's try - 'cos our shops was open 'til midnight you know, so we went up to the Blue and she said, let's try some eels for dad. So we went and got them live you know, we bought them live from these trays. I don't know what she bought. Some. And
 
- the man just cut the heads off and slit them and chopped it and you'd got to cut the pieces off, it was chopped to a point. When we got home this bag was wriggling. Mum said, I can't touch them. I said, neither can I. So we had to wait. Poor dad didn't 
g
et his eels. We - we had to wait 'til these bits stopped moving. Could you - oh - I couldn't - truly neither of us could touch them. I don't know what dad had, but we couldn't cook them. Not then. Oh no, we wouldn't touch anything like that. I've never ta
sted them. Have you? What - live ones? Did they - our man - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 Mansie's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 it was, you know, eel and pies, they - he just chopped the head off, slit the middle, took the middle out and then chopped it in bits. - But not - oh no, you cook it with - but we couldn't
 touch 'em because they were moving. Oh we had - yes. Poor mum. 'Course that was when we got more affluent. Probably I - don't know that I was at work, 'cos I wouldn't have been - there. But I - I was at work at -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would any of the family be working by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no, I was the - I was the first one. And I went to work at thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Why do you think that you were a bit better off then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I don't know. Perhaps I was working to bring in this four shillings, three and nine, sorry. Three and nine. I don't know why.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you ever have rabbit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh - no, we didn't ever have rabbit. But - my dad one - I must have been a bit bigger, he hadn't taken me, we'd got the other children. - It's only when I was alone he used to take me out, over to t
he stables. But - mum was expecting - well anyway we were doing something in the front room, I was there with her. And he came in, he came in with a sack, he'd been to the stables and he came in with a sack. And mum was on her knees seeing to this fire in
 the front room. What I was doing - but I was there by her side, and he said, here you are Mouldy, here's a present for you. And the sack moved. She fainted. Anyway she had the baby in the night. Oh. It was a black rabbit. Alive. It was a live rabbit.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did he get it from the market?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I don't know, I wouldn't know, she wouldn't have nothing to do with it. Well she wouldn't, she was - she'd collapsed. But could you - well, he'd got no sense. I mean he knew how - how far she was. Oh don't - so don't ever talk to us indoors about rabbits.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you keep any sort of pets then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Or hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. No, nothing at all. Whatever we had was her - garden. She loved her garden. Only a little pocket handkerchief. Flowers and the grapevine that went under the glass that went round to the outside lav.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about the long garden you were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6104996\charrsid3306671 talking}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh that was in Southwark Park Road. Long at the front. That's flowers. Yes. That's flowers. Well there was a long row of cottages a
nd they all had the front garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Why do you think she didn't grow potatoes there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I don't know, I don't think we thought about it. It only came - they only came up during the war. You see what I mean, we hadn't - thought of that then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. We were hit on the knuckles with his knife, if dad was there. I'm talking about weekends. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What if he wasn't there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, well I - I wouldn't know, I've forgotten probably. We might have be
en feeding the children and it didn't matter. But Sundays - it was very respectful, if you - if - no elbows on tables either. No. And if - if you made a noise, he would rap you with his knife. Yes. Not to cut you but just rap you on your knuckles. He was 
very strict in a way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said that you had to finish everything didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh yes. Yes. Yes, it was him, not - mum. He'd say, right, it's Sunday school time, get off down to the Central Hall, right. And we'd all trip off to the Central Hall. Come back and find your cold greens waiting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Could you choose at all what was put on your plate then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. No. No. So that leads me to say that Sundays we did have greens with our dinner. Yes. Where we didn't during the week, when mum and us children only. But Sundays evidently was a full dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Wasn't any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 If you wanted the salt or something like that could you ask for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I don't know as we had any. I don't think we thought of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Some people say you should ask for it and some that you should wait until you're offered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Pass the salt. Yes. Yes, no I don't think we ever thought of it. Well I don't think it was on the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You say you had to sit in an upright manner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about holding your knife and fork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh well - I wouldn't know because they - we all went down in steps and stairs and you couldn't expect the children to be - perfect. But - we all sat - and I - we still sit, you'd be surprised how 
I notice my brothers and sister were all upright. I hope I am still. But that is a point. It - it does reflect on your whole life, if you're trained early enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have to ask to leave the table?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, Sundays. Sundays when dad was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But you could go when you'd finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, always, yes. Can we get down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Could you bring a book or anything like that to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. There was no room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 There was just room for you all to sit round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, we all made our 
seat round this big table. And we nearly always had somebody else. Yes - either - any of us could take - have a friend in. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would your parents ask friends in or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Not a lot, they would call in, any neighbours, they would call in - up the 
road I remember them. They - mum never minded, you'd always have your tea with us, a - a cup of tea and a biscuit, there might be a biscuit there, some of - that's when Kit was at work, we got biscuits cheaper. But - no - neighbours would always have a we
l
come, put it like - there was something about the home, it was home - not a house. That was the point with mother. It was home. Oh come on in. And - there was something about it that - it - it was welcoming. Well I thought so. Yes. Yes. Just the same ther
e. And I'm always in a mess.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said you and your mother both served the meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Well mum would be serving and I would take it in, give that to Kit, give that to dad, give that to this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have to serve him first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, sometim
es - he - you know, he didn't want to - he would - what now - when did he want - oh - no, that's why he - he - he didn't want - his batter. Now why did he want his batter different? Oh because dad wanted his batter first. He started with his batter puddin
g
 first, dry. And he had to have that. Then he would have his plate of - dinner. Yes. Well I've heard of Yorkshire people having it - yes it is, Yorkshire people have it first. To fill them up first isn't it? I think so Well dad did too. I know there was s
omething that was - we were never together. And in his swivel chair and he had it on his own, more or less. And we never sat in that chair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 The youngest ones sat at the table did they or separately?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, all at this table. All at the table. There was a high chair at this end when mum did come in.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But she didn't really usually have time to sit down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. We did - we didn't bother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You feel that she didn't really eat as much as the others, just eating scraps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, but probably we got as much. I mean because I know all the bit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 
s I've had po}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 ked into me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But she wouldn't sit down with a proper plateful?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. We never sat down. I don't think I ever did either. And it's - it's the same habit now. When this gang - the 
Gardner gang come. You see you're - you're here getting the food and you're giving it to them and they say, now look, come and sit down here. I can't, I've got to go and get things ready. Which you have to. And I think the habit still hangs. Although I'm 
alone. It's nice to see the gang. And I'm back to the young days, as I say, the years have fallen away and you're just feeding the - the mob. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 Did your parents say that if another child hurt you, you should hit back or not?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. For one th
ing I think because we were always together in our own house. And there was no scrapping like there is with my four grandchildren. They do scrap. Little girls at that. But I never remember us scrapping. Not me, the - with the boys, I honestly never rememb
er them scrapping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did they bring you up to behave towards them in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I don't know, I can't remember - I can't say - it was just natural with us. We - we helped one another because we were such a - a - a close family, can I say that? 
We - we felt we were - just ourselves, I - I can't explain it. The same now, I wouldn't have anyone say a word - mind you, my sister, I'm annoyed with her, the one in Africa, really annoyed, but I wouldn't let anyone say anything about her. The - she's a 
n
aughty girl. I mind her children when they're here. The - the girl is eighteen and she's been expelled from Felixstowe college. I - the headmistress wrote - phoned me all about it and asked me to write to her mother as well as the official. I though, oh, 
I
 can't let Mabel know that I know. So I wrote an ordinary letter telling all about my son going to America. Just a normal letter. And I haven't heard a word from her. Now, phoning my - Glad, another sister, phoned her. She said, well you'll never get anyt
hing from Mabel, you know how selfish she is. I said, well - she's not, she's Mabel. She said, yes, but she always has been selfish, she was mum's spoilt baby. But it's surprising.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you think your parents brought you up to behave towards them in some special way? What did they expect of you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. We did it - without being told. I can only say that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 How would you put the way of behaving towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well, I - I can only give the instance of me telling dad to get up in my bed. And it's
 the same with all the children, we did it, they were ours. And we wouldn't let one of them cry or do anything. I know that with my brothers. Bert now is the one that was born in the war, 1916 or '17, I don't know, one of the years, it's odd years, '17, I
'm the even one, or the odd, and they're the even. If the year is odd - well anyway - that is the point - with Bert, he's just the same. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 
Very, very thoughtful to everyone of us. I mean and you can't say - I mean, I'm an old dear really, and yet he comes over and - oh, he says, Lou. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
You know, and he's so thoughtful. Both my kids are too. Mind you, I could kill 'em sometimes. My two. But - but us as a family, we only thought we were - it was us. And - I - what did I do. I mean, I - I used to help mum. We just 
did behave - you know, how we would want to behave, I mean, when she - had her baby - one of the babies, she'd only just had it, well anyway - early in the morning I got up to see to her and she said, oh Lou, help me outside. Oh, I said, you're not suppos
e
d - I think I was at work - I said, oh you shouldn't be up even. She says, oh I must get outside, let me lean on you. And I did, she leant on me, went all round the back and around to the outside toilet. It was just one of those things, you did help one a
nother in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What sort of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well they were very proud of us. And I mean that. Mum has told - 'cos dad died first, two years - few years }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 before}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  her - and she told me, she said, oh,
 she said, look at all your lovely children you've got, the whole lot, she said, I am proud of you lot. Stocks as good as money. Yes. I - and I think that was general in that working class district of London with us. I mean, we were no different to the ot
hers in the road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did they think that some things in life were specially important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. No, except that - I'll tell you this, when she's having all these children, she's telling me afterwards she said, I tried to get dad to stop it. She says, I t
ried to get dad to take care, she'd had about fourteen you know. So he said, heavens, he said, that is only for prostitutes, anything like that. And he wouldn't dream of it. So she still had her fifteen kids. That was the old Victorian man. We did - I did
 
resent that. At the time. Yes. Yes. But of course I still loved him. We - we did - really think a lot - we - I tell you, we were all round his bed when he died, and we - and I mustn't - but we did all - we were so upset really, but - when the funeral was 
o
ver we never stopped laughing. No. Well they were so many of us, with all our appendages. And our husband's there. I said, to him, oh I don't want you there. I said, we haven't arranged for you. So he said, well I thought a lot of your mum, I want to come
. Oh, I said, well if you want to come well and good. And he did. But - it was a riot. We all of us had decided we're going to die in solitude. We're not going - all the girls rather. Glad and Bags. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 NR. No. We never 
did. No. Never - not in the house. No. And - I don't swear, I do say a damn and a blast sometimes, I don't - I feel awful at the moment but I don't swear, we never did at home, ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Your father would have been very strict if you had have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. None of us - did. And I - and the - the kids, they all - the whole lot are very good. All my brothers. They are -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did your parents expect a lot of respect from you would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. It was always - we would let dad have it first
. And we said it too, we say, oh well, we'll - wait 'til dad comes in, let dad have his pick. That was - it wasn't it was told to us at all, it was just - it came natural I think because we only thought of us as a team. I can only say that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would you say that you got your idea of how to behave from both of them or that was one more important than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No, from my mother. From my mother. Dad was on the strict side, he knew what was right and what was wrong in his eyes, he would - as a matter
 - since we're older, I - he was wrong to leave my mother like - got three girls, he was so mad. He really was mad Terry having the only boy, and he kept on and he'd got his boy. Three girls and a boy he's got. He's thrilled. Really thrilled.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Can you tell me what a birthday was like as a child? Did you have presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Not when I was young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Anything special to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, we would have an orange. Well I'm talking about when I was young, but - of course, when the war came things were dif
ferent - the first war - things were different and then I began to go to work you see, I started work. Money was easier. I had my own threepence a week pocket money, but apart from that - there would be an orange there you could have and it was for your b
irthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Would you have a little sort of birthday party?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. No. No. I don't ever remember it. Whether she did for the others after I left I don't know. 'Cos Mabel was born - within a year before I left really. But - she could have done it for the others. But I don't remember. Not in my time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh well Christmas - there wasn't the toys - but there was oranges and nuts all in our stocking. That's it. And some Peak Freans biscuits. No, we never had anything 'til after the first war, then of course I was working, it was different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have a special sort of Christmas Dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 There was only a joint. Probably a bigger joint. We never had turkey or anything 'til after we were married, some of us. 'Cos we all
 went home - at Christmas - one of the days of Christmas, Boxing Day or Christmas Day, we couldn't all get together with our appendages. Husbands and wives. So - we did go home for one day. That was our meeting point for the whole family. And of course wh
en a parent dies - you've lost your home. And that is true. It's all right, I'm sunburnt. It is. Yes, it's stinging now. I've got warm sitting in here. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 You said your mother sang, did anyone else in the family sing?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no, only to join in with her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did anyone play an instrument?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Only - dad and his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 gramophone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 . Yes, one of these with a long horn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What sort of records did he play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh - oh - well mother's favourite was Lowly as a gentle lark, and she would sing it with
 it, you know. Dad's favourite was the - the - one of the military overtures. Light Cavalry. Light Cavalry Overture. That was his favourite, and it was on and on and on. 'Cos they - we didn't have a selection in those days you know, about half a dozen rec
o
rds for our Sunday evening. 'Cos that was after the - war, after I was working. He'd come back from the war and - he only got wounded in his bottom, and nothing happened, but he didn't go, not until '16 or '17, I'm not sure, 'cos he was older - and he'd g
o
t the children and he went to the war, came home in 1918. Right, she promptly produced another baby. Poor mum. We - we've laughed over it. I said, oh - oh I know what I would have done with him. She said, oh you couldn't, not with dad. Oh dear. Poor dad. 
But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 gramophone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  was after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, it was after the war. After the war.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Apart from singing when your mother was working did you make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes we did. All the old ones. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 Nirvana}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  and Pale hands I love, the Indian love lyrics they were then. Yes, we would sing them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When would that be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Sunday nights. In the front room. But of course mum and I, we weren't in there so much. As - as I tell you, people did used to come in, next door that side, and Annie Elston, she used to come in. They used to wrestle, her and my dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Not in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Fun. Yes. Yes. In the front room. Yes. Mum said, the silly old so and so. And we'd go outside. Yes, it was only fun with this girl next door. Well she was about thirty I should say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did the neighbours join in the singing then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. They had their own. They were quite - it was a kind of - universal in the area we were. There were some more people over the road. Very friendly with her mum
 was, she used to come in, woman, and she always used to call her Lou, my mum, she knew her when she was a girl and her name was Kit. But she always used to call her Lou and if she'd see me out she'd say, tell Lou I'll be over tonight, or be over so and s
o
. Yes. Yes, neighbours did used to come in - just for a cup of tea. Not Sunday - I'm talking about with dad Sundays, but for in the week always come in to the kitchen with the scrubbed table and cup of tea. She was always ready with her tea. You know, for
 anyone to come in, make a cup of tea. Which is - carried on with all of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, only balloons. Yes. That kind of game.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No cards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Dominoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Oh he was a draught player. He
 was a draught player. Draughts. Yes. Yes. It was - of course - one of the neighbours used to come in. I've forgotten their name - Vi - the girls was Vi, don't know what - Bill I believe he was - he'd come in and play draughts with dad. He did get me on i
t out in the kitchen but I got fed up. No, we didn't have - no cards. There were never cards in the house. I've got them here and I still think they're unlucky. Yes. 'Cos mum said they were Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were there any books to read in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 All the - the Dickens, there was Dickens and there was Wells - H.G. Wells there was. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I've still got some. Old. Yes, yes, we had books to read. But we didn't have a lot of time. But there were if I could - I would want to - I wasn't to read my Shakespeare again, I've got it here, the complete works.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have Shakespeare as a child then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes, we used to go to the Old Vic - from school. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did your parents ever read aloud?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Mum did. Mum did. To me -
 we were - we'd often sit alone at night. Each side of this range, yes. And - she would read. But I - I liked my own reading too. And then of course we would talk. I think it's in us, to talk. I think you get worse when you live alone too. Well I am. I do
n't know that I was a very talkative when I was young. A bit on the shy side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But your mother liked talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. She would talk to me all about her childhood and her work, yes. When she first went to work guess what she did? Before she marr
ied. As a girl. A tinsmith. In one of the factories. In Tower Bridge Road. Yes. Yes, and she could solder. If any of the neighbours wanted anything soldered she would do it. Well even my boys can't solder, nor could dad. Yes. She was a - she called hersel
f a tinsmith and she used to tell me what she used to do. At this Tower Bridge Road factory. Of course, but she married and - I suppose she was eighteen when she married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 She didn't have any other jobs before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, just - she was a
 tinsmith at Tower Bridge Road. I suppose that's where she met dad, I don't know. I've forgotten. And I can't ask her now can I? Poor mum. Oh there's lots of things I want to ask. Oh - wish and wish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have newspapers in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Or magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. We didn't have them. They weren't - much about then, not pre-war. No, we didn't have papers. Our life was all work. I meant - I don't mean work but I mean always on the go. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you remember a funeral in the family as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh yes. Our twins.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Can you tell me what happened? Was there a big gathering?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh no. Nothing. We had the - the - the hearse drew up and it had the little white coffin, the both - you tell how tiny they was, the one little white co
ffin, mum and dad were sitting behind, I think mum and dad. I don't know anything about - I mean I didn't go. But that went off, this little white coffin. And so far as I know it was buried with another person, an adult which was a thing that was done in 
those days. Mum told me that. But I only saw this little white coffin - one white coffin, so they put the two babies in the one coffin. And it was small under the man's sitting and it went off. That's all I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So you don't remember a funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Not a - not a big gathering, no. We had no sorrow at all. In the family. Never had any, not until dad died in - what - '54. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 The grandparents had died much younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes, but they'd all died - except granddad died in 1916, he died in - i
n the war, 1916, but I don't know, only mum went. Only mum went, it was in the war. It was her father. Fred Joy. He was a man with a walrus moustache you know. And I used to hate it to have to kiss him. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 With this walrus - and of course there was only me do
ing the running around, pre-war, I was the oldest you see then, and - only me - oh run down to granddad, Drummond Road, cut off of - yes, and - then of course he was ill and - I used to hate having to go, go and see how granddad is. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I used to detest it. And then he died. And that's all I remember. It wouldn't have been much of a funeral anyway. Not with granddad on his own, and mum with no money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did he ever visit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh yes. He used to come down, and I used to say - say goodbye to all of us with his walrus moustache. Yes, poor dear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You mentioned the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 uncle,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  were there any other relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. They - the - one - mum's sister had a pub in City Road, I used to go and visit as a little girl, mum used to take me brother. Because she'd got
 this pub and we'd walk it nearly all the way to City Road, up - right the far end at the Angle end, With - Witherick Arms. Well anyway whatever it was - we would walk there because Aunt Daisy would give us some money. But mum would take her - took her on
e
 of them old fashioned knife machines, 'cos aunt Daisy being in the pub with snacks, probably needed this, where you put the knife in and did the handle. Mum took her that, she said, let's take this to Aunt Daisy. And we did. And of course actually it was
 
only to get some money probably, see her sister and get some money, but - but oh I - I had an Aunt Minnie, that's - we're all named after these different aunts, Minnie and Mathilda. Anyway Aunt Minnie, she used to help mum I think, which I wouldn't know w
h
en I was a - when she had the two babies after me, 'cos I must have been too small then. But - or when she was having the babies, Aunt Minnie would take me in another flat in these buildings. And she had a little machine that used to go that way. Have you
 
ever heard of it? Yes. Instead of your work going through, the - the work used to come out that way. She used to machine, yes. Used to put lace on the edge - I don't know what on - and she used to hold the lace and I was fascinated by seeing this work com
e
 out that way. And she would hold the lace and it would be stitched on. I'd love to - love to have the machine. To see it again. But I've never forgotten Aunt Minnie and her machine. Poor Aunt Minnie. Yes. Yes, there - there were aunts, another aunt - I u
s
ed to go over and see with mum. Another aunt at East Ham. Oh - the children of the aunt in the pub when they were on holiday from school she used to send them to this aunt at East Ham. All country in those days. They used to spend their summer holidays th
ere. And then when they were there - mum would take us - take me over. I'm saying us, I can only remember me going. She might have had a baby but I've forgotten. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 
But I know we used to go to this aunt in East Ham.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You had a holiday there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No,
 we only went to see. No, just to see the children and to see her sister and perhaps Aunt Daisy would be there taking the children I think. I - I wouldn't know, I've forgotten. Yes, we - we got about on our own feet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about on your father's side, were there any other contacts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, only his sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you see anything of her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no, they're all dead. No, no. No. No, he used to go over. He used to go. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  leave us behind, he used to see his family on a Sunday - a brother and a sister. See, every fortnight he - yes, every other week he would go and see these.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 They came to you the other week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, only the brother. Only the brother came to us. Uncle Bill. No, the sisters we never saw. That is probably - which I didn't know an
ything about - that was mother was harbouring a resentment. We never knew. It was kept fairly well hidden from us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 They kept their feelings to themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. Yes, and it's down with us too. You'd be surprised what I could tell you about my life. And not saying a thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 It's strange to think your mother talked to you so much in the evenings and yet kept these sort of things to herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well, any resentment, we would talk of normal things about our own life and her family and her
 - and relations with her husband and - that, but she would never say anything nasty about it, and I mean she wouldn't say anything about Aunt Till or the others. Which she did resent I found - out after dad was dead.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 She told you afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh
 yes. Yes. Yes she did, she told - I think, so far as I remember she - she wrote to her when her husband died. She wrote to her and told her - a few things. Oh, I said, you didn't, not Aunt Till. Yes, I did. I kept - kept it in check all these years. And 
I do see mum's point of view. Poor dears, they're both dead now. I wish I'd got them here now. Oh I would, I love them such a lot. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You say neighbours came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were you ever taken out to visit neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. They came int
o our house. Our home. I can only say that. The - it was always a - a welcome. There was a - an atmosphere. When you opened the door there was - and she kept it nice, just carpet up the hall, you know, just with the wood at the side, but nice and bright a
n
d clean. And I - I don't say I followed the same trend but it happened that anything you see with me is bright. The telephone, anything. If there's a choice it's red. My carpet. Yes. I think it - it's just born in us that way. We - I tend to - if there's 
a choice, right, we'll have the red one. It's only - it is - I think it gives a more welcoming appearance. Mum's did anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did she have pictures at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh don't talk about pictures. Yes, dad did. Yes. Pictures. He sent for Pears pictures. Pear
s annual at that time, long thin ones, all round the front room wall. And - I wanted them when he died, but it was so quick that she'd got to - well - the Council gave her notice to quit and offered her these different flats until she chose the right one 
and then in the end she left everything behind. My pictures and all. And I wanted my photo. Yes. I'll tell you what else was lost - left, that I wanted I'm sorry, not that it matters now, all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 horse }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 brasses, of dad's. Leather - all leather saddles, not saddles, the strappings.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 From his job you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. And the - the - the horse bridle. He went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did she leave them in the home then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Well he used to go in for - I never - I don't know - I mean, I never went - he used - the Regent - 
the horse and cart parade or Horse Parade at Regents Park. And he went in for that. Yes, and he'd got all these brasses and polished them up. And they were kept in his bedroom cupboard. All lost. Well - you see, the family scattered. If we'd would all bee
n
 near we could all have kept our eye on them. But we were all scattered, everyone scatters now don't they, I mean - they live at Surrey and - and they're all South London. One at Sevenoaks, one - two at Dulwich. One in New Zealand, one in Africa. Where ar
e
 the others? Catford. See we're all scattered, me here, I'm the only one here. Two in Bromley, South. Well - you can't keep your eye on things. No. Which I wish now that - but does it matter. I'd like to put a match to all this. Truly. No I mean that. Yes
.
 Well what's going to happen if I die, if I - what happened if I died in the night. The whole place is furnished. Yes. Beds in every room up there. Oh yes, you couldn't leave it - well I shouldn't be here actually but - I - all I saw when I saw this house
 as opposed to the tiny cottages in Colchester, oh I'll be able to get me piano in. Mistake. Real mistake.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You didn't have a piano as a child then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no. I bought that for mum - for Mabel. And that's why I've got it, it was mine. Mum - when dad 
died and she had to go she said, oh you take your piano back now Lou. So Lou's got the piano and - no one plays it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You can't play yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, only pick out - my husband used to. My - my brothers do. They - when they come over they get on it. 
Two of them rather. Only by ear, but it's music, it's a noise. Yes. My husband used to. I've picked out some tunes, but I do mine with - you know - like that. But my grandchildren - do all their fingers. Yes. Her mother - the mother - my son's - my eldest
 
son's wife is a pianist, she's got all her medals. And it's come down in her children because - where I go like that they - they really - have got the touch. You can tell the difference when they're artistic can't you? Oh dear, she's only seven, young Car
ol, and she plays. I think we'd better stop. All right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No, we had nothing. We had no holidays. I never had a holiday, until after I married. Then for two years we had a holiday with a - a motor bike and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6110570\charrsid3306671 sidecar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 , we went to Leysdown, had a chalet and my son was a tiddler. And then I didn't have a holiday then - until - another twenty years. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 
Till - the first holiday was when my mother-in-law died. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 '54 mum - '54 dad, '56 my mother-in-law, '58 my mother, we went away the next year, '59. 1959.'s my first holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you never go for outings to the seaside then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh - well, with the Sunday school, Southend. And an outing with the Sunday school to Riddlesdown, which used to be. Surrey - just outside London. Chislehurst and Riddlesdown. And the days outings. Oh I wouldn't say you didn't have days outings But not -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 With your parents ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You never went for a days outing with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What was Southend like in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Better than it is now. Or better than it was when my husband and I used to - when we got the car and - we went down. We used to go out Saturdays then. And then we went to Scotland - for our holiday - first holiday after the children - when I had the firs
t child, we never - holiday for Peter, 'cos he was born - the year war broke out you see. Not that that mattered, but - I don't think we thought of it. And as for pre-war we - well you had to work every day didn't you, in the olden days I mean. And you - 
I mean, if you had a day off you were stopped, not like now, stay in bed if you got a cold. I think that's - well I wouldn't say we didn't expect it, we never knew they existed. Put it like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What did you do when you went with the Sunday school outing to Southend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh you had to go around with the crowd didn't you. I don't remember what we did. No, I don't remember. No. No. No, it wasn't. And it was train anyway, train to there, and then train - course it's - don't forget you were march - walki
ng to the station, there weren't the transport in those days, you walked to the station. We walked to the station - London Bridge I think to get to Riddlesdown. So that half your day was taken up with marching, and coming home again. Anyway it was an outi
ng. We thought it was wonderful. Yes, yes. Then of course I did used to go to the Old Vic with the school. I liked it. I like Shakespeare, these }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 plays.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3306671  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And I like seeing a play. When I did have T.V. I haven't got it now. I couldn't afford the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 license}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 , five 
years ago, so I packed up the T.V. So - but I like listening to Shakespeare and I check with my - book when there's a play on. And I like going, I've been to the rep theatres where they do - put them on. Yes, I like them live theatre.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did anything special happen on Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What - in our schooldays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Your father was working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Working - all Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You wouldn't have been at school on Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, wasn't at school. I'd be - that's when the children stayed in bed, with thei
r biscuit crumbs. I think. I must have been at work. I - I - no, I mean I must have been out at work. If Kit was bringing in crisp - biscuit crumbs Kit was working This was - wartime. Ah before then - when I was at school, I don't remember a lot of - but 
I know - dad was at work and I probably I was helping mum. 'Cos we couldn't do the shopping, not 'til dad came home with his sovereign. Which was a sovereign in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did your mother carry on working on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, no machining. Oh no. We didn't do anything on a Sunday. But she did cook. She wasn't - that far for religion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Could you play games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well the children played in the garden. And I don't know what I did, I've forgotten I - I was just with her. That's all I can remember
, being with her always. If we went out shopping I was with her standing behind her skirts. I always stood behind her too, hanging on. Hanging on. I was shy - in those days. Probably because I only mixed with her. Could it be? I mean I didn't mix with chi
ldren so much. 'Cos I was away from school a lot. Well, every time she was - I don't know when I - the scarlet fever I was in hospital, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  in hospital and then away for - each time she had - was in bed with a baby. Always three weeks. One - one week to help her when she was up, because she never had doctors, that's the point, not when I - in my young days.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have to wear special clothes at all on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, we never had any. I only had mum's cast offs. Yes. I - I do mean that. I never had anything new at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said she made the clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
She made our clothes, yes. Cut down from her. Yes, pass them down, yes. And she would make them. The pinnies, we always had clean pinnies - as she called them. She was very industr
ious. Very. Because that's before she had to do the shirts, I can always see her working. Sewing. Doing my pinnies. And - and then the babies coming along.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did they go to church or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Who - mum and dad? No. No. Not mum and dad. Send us. We alw
ays did go, I mean, I was godmother to all the children. Yes. Always, as soon as she was up she went to the churching and the christening, and I was godmother, to the - oh, Claire Hall the church was. Chapel I suppose it was. She never went over the road 
to the church. Claire Hall we used to go. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That's the Sunday school you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Well - there - there was lots in London, - this Claire was Sunday school and church. The Methodist was on the corner of the High Street, Methodist. And then when she was fed up with that, or dad was fed up, send me down to the Central Hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 They switched you around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. Change around. Yes, it depended. But we always used to go to Claire Hall for the Christening. And I would hold the baby while she had the churching and then when we'd go to the other place for the - for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 christening}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  I would be godmother. It's - it's surprising isn't it to - that the vicars would allow that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Because you said they were married in Church of England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, they were married at St James' church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 They never went back to that after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, no. Well it was further away. It was further away. Yes. Farther away. I don't know proper English. I - I'm a cockney.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When grown ups were talking did your parents let you talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Bee seen and not heard. That was his - and he used to go like that to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Hold up a hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Seen and not heard. Then when we were older, he used to say, now, know nothing. He - we're a family that don't talk. Because he use
d to say, know nothing. You'll never get into trouble. And we - we followed him. We talked to ourselves like - the Gardners as a whole, we - we talk but we don't repeat outsiders - anything we hear. I think it must have been dad saying - know nothing. And
 of course he said it with a - as a Cockney, know nuffin. Real Cockney - Londoner.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When you had these neighbours in did you join in as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. No, we weren't allowed to. Don't know why. Mother used to hit us on the head with a thimble.
 Never - not to hit us. That is why I'm sore I think. Yes. No, we knew what was wrong you see. I mean, she - kept - you know - held the candle to dad really, that's - I can only put it like that. And I think we all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What do you mean by that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yo
u know, she would - you know, dad didn't come in 'til late, and she would sort of - keep things happy. None of us would intrude, she'd say, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 be quiet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When he came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh yes. Yes. We were quiet because of him. Well the others - I don't think I d
id make much noise at that time. I was outside working, which she did, really, I mean I did used to get my knocks on the head with the thimble. Not hard but it's enough to make me feel sore now - although I'm old. We've laughed over it. So - she's laughed
 too, she did laugh with us. She said, why didn't you tell me it was sore? But at that time I had it scragged back with a bow on the top and it was that bow on the top that made it sore as well. Why didn't you tell me? Poor mum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 We were talking about Sundays when we broke off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. Carry on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You were saying how you went to the Sunday schools at Claire Hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And that you went on outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were there any other sort of activities attached to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. Not - only when we got to - fourteen, then we joined the Girls Guild.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Can you tell me about that, - what you did in that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, we'd only sit - there was a teacher - Miss Rudd, we just would sit round talking and - she 
would talk to us, because being a Methodist chapel, as it was, the end of the road one, there wasn't any - no that was the Methodist, the Methodist as we called it. Claire Hall was near Southwark Park Road. But - the - Methodist chapel, we weren't there t
o
o long, we had to go down to the Central, I don't know, something mother got in her bonnet. But we did all troupe off, with me in charge. I - I still never went up to the top to find that picture - never mind. - I'd love to have shown you that picture of 
me standing behind the whole lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What did they teach you about then at this class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Only religions. Religion more or less, yes. Bible readings. - bible readings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You had to learn things by heart?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. That was all. Yes. - And Miss Rudd
 used to - talk. And - no it was only just sort of a Guild. I - I really can't say any more, because by the time I got round to boyfriends I'm afraid the Central Hall didn't - come in. The others went. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That was Sunday afternoon again was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No, that was in the week, we used to go to the - the Guild as the - it was called. But - you didn't go to there 'til after you were at work. And of course I was at work at - thirteen. At that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you ever join a choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. I couldn't sin
g for toffee. I'd love to have been. Would have loved to. Because we all used to join in at home with mum and her hymns. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 Tell me the old, old story. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Up from the grave he rose. She used to choose those that had a - a long - a crescendo, you know what I mean? I - up or down. All the while she was treadling. Poor mum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about a temperance club, you said your father actually supported temperance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you know if he joined a club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. I don't know what the boys did because t
hey'd be at - well that all came in - not me so much 'cos I was that much older and I had left school and by the time I'd got to eighteen - oh I'd love to show you one of my dad's letters from France. Yes, you'd love to see it because you've love his - yo
u
'd love his writing. It was - perfect script. A roundy writing. Even when he was old it was just the same. And when he was a little boy, 'cos he was at work at then, so he said, but when he was a little boy at school - he got a prize, he won a - one of th
ose - desks that lift up - for handwriting. And it was still the same. Yes. I - yes, I would - I would like you, because I don't think anyone knows the meaning of writing as it is today. Oh yes. And this desk, oh it was wonderful.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He always kept that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. Only the square thing, the old fashion. My youngest brother's got that, when he died, and all the certificates were kept in it. But - he really was perfect writing. You tell me some questions, now I've got rid of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You say he didn't go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Neither did my mother. She had no time, I don't think. But she was - she kept us at it. And she practiced it, with her neighbours.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You told me about her going to pray with the neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 She did it in other ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. Yes. I can't tell you - she - there's another neighbour over the road, very friendly, we - we knew her when we lived in the buildings, there was only me and another baby, she knew this one and she always called her the wrong name, 'cos she
 was Kit. My mother, was Kate and Kit for short. And she always called her Lou, so of course the Lou used to go round so - but - she went and helped her when she was dying and ill. Well - not to do anything but just to comfort her. She - she - she only - 
I
 wouldn't say she was religious but she practiced religion. Giving us - she does - she did give us a lead of - helping people, which we all do. Well - I hope I do. But I feel that with my sisters. I don't know about the one - the in-laws, but the boys are
 very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you ever have prayers in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. Not with us. But she knew we were all went to Sunday school and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 It sounds as if your father may have been a bit more religious?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes - Dad. Yes they had got that - whether is 
was there - bringing up was stopped when their parents died. Could have been because they both - well no, mum had a father, but they both - their - dad lost mum and dad and I never knew a grandparent there on the paternal side. And mother was always awful
ly fond of her mother. When I was twenty-one she gave me a - a cross, she said, oh do take care of it Lou. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 Mum}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 gave it to me before she died. Oh - yes. I have still got, I've never worn it. 'Cos I'm frightened to. No, I'm not - I mean in case I should lose }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 it.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 It's upstairs in a - box with all little oddments. Got no jewellery as - as such. But - they were very - I would say they were devoted to one another. They never showed it. Well they didn't to us. Probably - too many children, no time. And of course - 
with dad - long hours of working in those days. From five thirty in the morning 'til nine at night by the time he got home. Anyway, it was fun.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Then where do you think he got the temperance ideas from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I don't know. Could it have been his upbringing - I've never thought about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He was always temperance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. We didn't have anything in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But did he belong to any temperance orders or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. He never did - went anywhere. Neither did mother. She did w
hen she was left a widow, she joined the thing at her church then. But - but while they were alive she never - they - neither of them went anywhere. Except dad went off for a holiday. Walking. Yes. - Oh yes. I think mum - there was two more babes - childr
e
n with me. And he just went off. Mum told me in the morning, she said, oh dad's gone off, he's gone to Paddock Wood with Uncle - Uncle Ted. He wasn't an uncle, was a good friend, who was always in when he wanted. They've gone to Paddock wood, they're walk
ing. And they walked to - no, not to Paddock Wood, to Goudhurst, near Paddock Wood. And then - they walked home as well. What a holiday. Can you imagine the modern youngsters doing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 How many days were they away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 A week I think. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What do you think they did then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I don't know. They just went walking down to Goudhurst to Mrs Blunts, I still know where she went - where he went to. Mum told us. And he talked about it. About how Mrs Blunt looked after them. Then they started their trek back. What a holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Was he fond of the countryside then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. I think we all are. It's handed down to all of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That's the only time that he went off for a holiday like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. I wouldn't know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You never had any did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. We never went - we never went out. Not until I got older, and went to these days outings with the Sunday school. To Riddlesdown.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Can you tell me if he took an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, no, not an interest. But he was a Liberal, whi
ch was in those days - 'cos it was - in those days it was - our - area, was bounded by Brom Road, Cargom and Cargom was the Liberal candidate. Candidate. And - he was - oh he was very - whatever that was, at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you know why he was a Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, I don't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He didn't talk about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. He wasn't home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He didn't belong to the party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did he do anything active?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Like canvassing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Not like me, I'm always out. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, oh no. Mum neither.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When did you start taking an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well after I married. I did it really to be opposite to my husband. 'Cos my husband was a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 Socialist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  like his father. I used to create because we were living in the middle of a - working area, Fords, which were all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 Labour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 people, and I was so annoyed. I said - I used to lay down the law and said, I'd any sense - I said, I'd shut that firm down. And he used to get on to me. So right, I joined the Conser
vative party. And I've been working for them ever since. I'm on the committee now. Executive at Clacton. Crazy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you remember a man called Alfred Salter when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh Doctor Salter, he was our doctor. Yes. A doctor. Mum used to go
 to him. But of course I had to be different when I grew up I registered - when I started work we just began the - 1916 I think - the health scheme. I joined the Hearts of Oak to be with dad. And - of course I had a different doctor, I didn't want to do t
he - Doctor Salter, he was a Labour man. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What did your family think about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh I think he was very good doctor. 'Cos mum always took the - children to get these little tiny bottles of medicine. Yes. Shilling a time. But - no, I - I've bee
n a kind of a rebel, I mean, I would do opposite. Well - I don't - 'course I don't know what politics were in those days. No, they weren't discussed at home, it's only when I thought for myself - saw what was going on, I decided that I didn't want the Soc
ialist, I - so I joined the Conservative party at home, and here, as soon as I got here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did your mother ever go out by herself to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Never ever. Never ever. And I could mean - really mean that. Well she'd got us children to do al
l her running around. The only time was when we were broke, she had - wasn't working that particular week probably, I don't know, and then we would go out to my aunt at - City Road, her sister - her younger sister, and - who had a public house and she'd s
ay, oh well, Aunt Daisy'll give us something. That was the only time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 A good meal you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. Yes. Not that we were hungry. But - probably she wanted money. I - I don't know what was in her mind then but she would say, let's go over to Aunt Daisy. And we would go to Aunt Daisy. I think she's only just recently died, Aunt Daisy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So she didn't really have any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. She had no interests at all, only with her family. She really was - well we all loved her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Your father got home late, would he always stay at home then or would he go out sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. Never went out. He never went out either. Not at all, ever. Usually - if he got home half past eight to nine he'd have his meal, he would sit for a little 
while and then he'd go to bed, 'cos he'd got to be up five in the morning, leave home at half past five, walk it to - Upper Thames Street, and start work at six. He was out on the road. But of course when I was a - more or less alone or with one other bab
y
, he did used to call in for us at Jamaica Road and - take us out. 'Cos mum wasn't working then. I don't know whether she wasn't allowed to in the buildings, or what. It was only when she - got short of money that she took up machining. I think that must 
have been started in - Southwark Park Road. Not in the buildings - Russell Scott. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So he never belonged to any working }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 men\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  clubs or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. Not at all, no. Neither of them ever went out, not to enjoy themselves. They would - dad 
would go out every other Sunday to his sister to tea. And mum never went out, only - now and again when she was hard pushed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That means he took no interest in sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He belonged to the Hearts of Oak?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. The insurance, yes. Only dad and I. St range isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did he just join because of the scheme?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, dad always belonged - that was his - insurance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Sort of sick club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, a sick club. And - and then of course when I had to join I - I don't think I ha
d to join 'til I was - 'til 1916. When the - Lloyd George scheme as dad used to call it came out, so - I - tagged on with the Hearts of Oak with him. And of course I put my sons into it too. Yes. Yes. Old habits die hard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What does that cover?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 N
o, it only covers death. Death. Yes, yes, just funeral benefits really, we weren't - we didn't have enough money to pay for a friendly society, a sick - sick club society. I think they had a sick club with it, but we just had the funeral benefits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No other savings things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Like boot clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh no. And - it wasn't - we wouldn't dream of - of - of - having anything without paying for it. I've got one son who does - or his wife - you know - the hire purchase, but the other son, he's - y
ou know - take after the Gardner's side, he wouldn't have anything without he'd saved up first and got it. Pay for it cash. I tried to instill into them - but poor Terry. I - you know, I think it's dreadful. Myself - that's - that's my view. But a lot of 
people - hire purchase, yes, I don't believe in it. Yes, but of course, money is different now isn't it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
You say that you never scrapped as children when you were playing, did you feel there was one of the brothers or sisters who was a particular playmate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. I was very much a loner. I was. But the others went in pairs. The boys were in pairs. Bert and Jim were usually together. Nobody got on a lot to play with the youngest one, Mabel. 'Cos they all - they come over here and say, well she was a 
spoilt brat. But - it - not that we're talking about her, only of her, because we - we love her just the same but - being the last baby she was thoroughly spoilt. Yes. Because there's generations between us, you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 So you really played by yourself then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. Well I don't know that I ever played. I - well I must have done when I was very tiny but I don't - well I still remember these - bus tickets, bent to stand up. I still remember that. So I must have had some playing time. But I'm talkin
g; about when I really - when the children came along, I was very much - always with me mother, do this, do that. And it was done without - it was done without question, we never - not like my grandchildren now, they turn round and say no, straight away. 
And she's only four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You could invite neighbours in to tea, were they allowed to come into the garden to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No, there was enough of them in the garden, but the women neighbours would come in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I mean children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Children, no, there wasn't any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But you said you could invite other children to tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes, we did - now I would have one girl who I was at school with, she would come in, Hetty. But - only to come in to see us. And she would stay to tea. We never made - mum never made 
any bones about it. And the boys the same. And by the time I was older, I think all that lot, they'd all got somebody there, perhaps girls and boys, but there'd be - dozens of - or it felt like dozens. But - no, then - one sister - one - the young - the -
 
the third sister, she - we went over to a cousins twenty-first birthday, you can tell how we're getting on, he was same with me, he's twenty-one so we went over, and - not mum and dad, only us children. And my third sister - she was - playing around with 
A
lec you know, laughing and talking. And the second sister was a bit jealous. And it - it was true, she was jealous. She married him. Second one. We couldn't believe it. But - it didn't work out. It never worked out - they were cousins. Never worked out. B
u
t - we - we laugh now about that and Alec. And Kit pinched him. Yes, it's - it's all good fun, was all, with us family. But - and I get on well with all the in-laws. They like - they all come over and they like coming. Oh it's good to get over here, we ca
n drop some crumbs. You can't in Kits.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Was she always much tidier do you think then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. Yes. She was very - she used to talk with a - plum in her mouth. Because I was really born in the - the slums, you know, along the riverside. And - it's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 surprising}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 - because dad was a real cockney. He - get me - something about his daisy roots. Forgotten what that is. But I always remember him saying me daisy roots. Yes, he - dad was a real Cockney. And - there's - there's somebody on the radio that's like h
im, I think, oh poor dad. But as a lot, they're - they're not too bad, real - I don't know about myself, I have got a horrible voice, but the others, they're not too bad to listen to. Probably because they're - another generation and we might have moved o
ut of the riverside slum. Could have been.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You tell me that your mother wouldn't let you play outside the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Play out in the street or anywhere. It was always indoors. They never - I don't think they would - well I don't think they wanted to
. I don't think it was the done thing in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Lots of children did play in the street didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. You're quite right, and lots of children those days had no boots on, no shoes. Well, mother was a bit choosy. I think perhaps that mig
ht have been. She - you know - she would say, don't you go up the other end of that - 'cos the market - it was in two halves, our street. And the other end led into the market. - And that was where the - poor - poor children - of course we were poor of co
urse, but they were poor, and they were without boots on. And probably she might have been choosy and - play in your garden. Which was quite all right, there's enough of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were there particular children that you remember her saying don't go and play with those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No, nothing by name. But you could see them. Up the road, I mean, near the market. No. We never went up that end anyway, you would cut through. Cut round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You'd avoid it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, avoid it. Go that way. Yes, I - I've never analys
ed that before but we didn't. It could have been because - they were so very poor, those other children. And we were poor but - I suppose mum didn't like to show it. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Could you go and visit your friend from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You weren't allowed to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. Well - it never arose because - our time was taken up in our own home. I don't think we ever wanted to. That - I think that must have been. Mind you, I do know - I resent it now, but I wasn't allowed - any playtime. But I - probably 
in the olden days you never thought of - playing, because before - you know in the eighteenth century or 17}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
 - no, nineteenth century, I mean the - the children used to work all the time didn't they, sweeps and whatnot. And I was only just out of that are
a wasn't I? Must have been that. There wasn't the - inclination to do anything else but live. Might have been.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When you were getting a bit older did you have any hobbies like collecting something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Stamps. I've still got them. I've still nev
er got around to doing them, finishing them off. Yet I was a collector or stamps then. But I couldn't get anything. I mean, I had no contacts. I was a very shy person, never having mixed with others. Then of course sewing - sewing and knitting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You did that as a hobby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. Embroidering. We were all with our needlework, yes. Yes. I had all my things stuck up at school. Darning and - they were still there with - when I took my children to see. Still on the wall. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you do samplers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Samplers - yes. Yes, they were on the wall. Louise Gardner. Oh dear, that's me. It doesn't seem possible that you could show your children. Yes. Yes. Of course the school was bombed - this war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You didn't do any gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. We were - well 
mum was a real gardener. That was our name and nature. She used to say that. And she loved her little bit of black garden. It was only black. Black dirt you know, and the pathway was black, no grass ever grew. But she loved her bit and her grapevine. I've
 still got - bit of it in the garden here Yes, cutting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you have your bit of garden where you sowed your own flowers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. There was only the one - square thing. I think my sideway is twice as wide as it was. Shame. When you think what sh
e could have done. She would have loved to have been here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. Only the cat. And she would always have two. She'd say, no they're lonely with only one. And she would have two new kittens. And it was fun, to watch the two. One - 
whisky and soda, two of them. Then of course poor Kit mangled the - the black one. Yes. Yes, we didn't have any other pets - at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When you were a little bit younger - you didn't go for walks while you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. In our schooldays. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And you didn't have a bicycle until the 1920's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You didn't take part in sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You didn't go to concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Or cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But you did go to the Old Vic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 The Old Vic. Quite right, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And the music hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. Now and again dad would take me. I've forgotten - why he was so impressed about this Tower Bridge, walking me over it, making me stand with one foot one side and one the other while it wobbled, horse and cart would go
 over, is because he used to tell me about when it was opened. And he was, you know, very thrilled about it. I think he went and saw it opened. Was 1892 or something like that I think. I think he must have been very small, but - and it stuck in his mind, 
and I think it that's why he was so thrilled to take me - to - see it. Yes. Or make me stand there. I used to hate it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You didn't have this pocket money until you started to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Started work, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 When you had this threepence you spent it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Ribbons and bows, a black - gloves and a big black bow - for me hair. Yes, and we never thought of spending it on other things. Well if we did it would only be a farthing. You know, an ounce of sweets at they were four ounces a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What about the pork chop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh that was when I was at work. Had some money left of my own. Yes. I would - treat meself on a Saturday night and come - come home with a pork chop instead of some sweets. Which I thoroughly enjoyed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said that your parents did share the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
They had the same - just the same few - real ones like Uncle Ted and - Mrs Dedman over the road who she used to know when she lived in the buildings. But apart from that only neighbours would come in, no real friends b
ecause we never visited. They - she - and dad would only ever visit their own relations.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Uncle Ted was the hunchback?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Was the hunchback, yes. And now - yes, he must have been older, and of course now I'm older I realize it was just - their kindn
ess that they let him - you know - come in to the home. 'Cos he had no family. And - it's part of their practical religion. Which they were. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 They were very, very nice.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 They didn't go out it visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said that apart from this wrestling with this girl it was mostly just talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 With the girl next door, yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Then you said that your family thought of themselves as working class? But that there was the other group that you said your mother described as rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. The - the other lot she would say, don't - don't go up the rough end. That was how she would say - the other half of Anchor Street. And we didn't want to because - we were I suppose a bit snooty. Must have been. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Can you repeat that story about your father needing to look for work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh - well, I can't tell you what the reason was. I was young. So something must have happened with his firm of - of O.B's as he used to call it, Upper Thames Street. Because there wasn't an
y work and he said to mum he was going down to see about some casual work at Hayes Wharf. And there was - well I don't know what happened with him but I have seen the line of men - all lining up and a ganger would come along and just point to one here or 
there, half a dozen perhaps, and the rest would have to turn away, no work, and I think poor dad came home each time. I don't think he ever got work. But it wasn't long. - Probably a week or so, when he was back at O.B's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But your mother felt very strongly about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
She was very strong, she thought it was dreadful him having to go and line up for casual work. Evidently dockers weren't thought much of in those days. Must have been. No, it must have been something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 What sort of jobs do you think were the most respectable to have then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 I don't know. 'Cos he did look up to the horse - there was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 horse keeper}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  at his firm and he did think a lot of this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 horse keeper}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
, but I don't know why, dad used to have to go in on a Sunday, evidently it was arranged because he used to walk me to Upper Thames Street. While he fed these blinking horses. Oh 1
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 He used to talk about this man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh - yes, he did at home, yes. But he used to know all the horses by name and hit them on the butto
cks you know, hello Daisy, hello - oh, and I was scared. Really scared. I still - 'til recently have - still have nightmares, and I've only traced it to that. Yes. I'd love to have told him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You say that the most important people in the district you think were the shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 To us, yes, the shopkeepers. And the doctors, because I know the doctor used to go - to the church. St James'.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Your parents knew a doctor personally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Doctor Hollins. Yes. He was a friend of theirs. A friend,
 yes. He would call in. Yes. If he was passing. And - but she used to take the children to - Alfred Salter. Doctor Salter, yes, the - you know - whether it was cheaper. Could have been, as he was a Socialist. Could have been cheaper. That - that could hav
e been the reason, I've never thought about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did they know any of the shopkeepers as friends?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. Not particularly. 'Cos they was all little shops, all round those back turnings. Go to Davies' and get so and so. Go to a - over the road and ge
t - ha'porth of jam. It's - you used to take these - potchet - you know, I mean, not china, but that grey stuff, jam jars, used to take that and get that nearly three quarters full for a ha'penny. 'Cos they used to sell - used to be sold in great big ston
e jars, and used to dive in with a spoon and get you out some. That was quite good. Yes. Ha'porth of jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Was there a lot of sort of chattering going on in these sort of shops do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, I don't remember. Don't remember that. Whether i
t was because I was young and didn't - with children you don't do you, not so much, listen or join in. I - because by the time I started work as a little girl - a little old girl - the others were coming along and they would do the running. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said that you weren't taught to curtsey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no. No. Nothing like that. The working class}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 es}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 . The Gardners. Yes. There were, as you say, all stratas. 'Cos we wouldn't mix with the rough lot. Because they were barefooted and - and we didn't mix with the 
upper classes. That was noticed as you pointed out, you know, in the church. When we went to St James'. Not that I know anything about - St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 Paul\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  or anything when any event took place. Because you - there were so many aisles there you had to fill in the aisles at the side. I mean, it was open to the public then. With any special occasion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 That's when your mother took you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes, for any occasion, yes. I - I can't tell you, it could have been the King dying. Or could have been the end of war or beg
inning of war, I don't know, but she would - she was quite happy - to go and sing her chants which I knew nothing about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You were saying about St James', that's where you sat in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 the middle}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Where we sat centrewards, yes. Yes. I can always see us going up to that side, centrewards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said that your mother took you occasionally when there was very few in the family and then she gave that up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes, it was given up. Yes. But - with any special event she would make a - a - an effort a
nd we would go. Would it be the weekend or not? I don't know because I should have been working if it was war, or should it have been King Edward dying. King Edward. '10. Well, perhaps that was it, the first one. I wouldn't know, I've forgotten.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said you didn't come into contact with any Irish people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. We never. Probably because we'd moved away from the riverside, Jamaica Road by then. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 We must have got away from - the docker's - docker's part. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Not that the - oh yes, they did, there was al
l buildings down there. Cherry Garden Street. There was all buildings. And little houses. Yes, I - we probably moved away. I can only explain it that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 The only contact with a Catholic you remember was this uncle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Now that was - in Jamaica Ro
ad on the riverside side. So probably that's why - probably that was why he met the Catholic wife. And of course they never change their religion, it's the Protestants that have to change. And that's what happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did the family disapprove of the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. No. No, we were all friendly - during the - the years we knew them - knew - met them. We never visited a lot. But - they must have visited at the time when Uncle Fred was ill, first ill. And also when he died. Why we had to have Uncle Fred 
in our front room I don't know. Surely they must have had a home? Don't know. Well, anyway I don't know that, but poor mum turned the wake away. Yes. Yes. I don't think I would have done that. I would have gone out and left them the house, if it had been 
me. In my own reasoning now I'm older, I should have - right, there's the house, you know, we can - we'll go out and leave you the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did your mother feel that your she was completely the same sort of social class as your father or did she feel there was some difference?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I don't know, no, I don't think so. No, I don't - there's been nothing ever said. She's only told us all about her upbringing. And - 'cos she knew nothing about the Devonshire home, she only knows the mother coming up, probabl
y when she married my grandfather. And it must have been sometime before because mum was the second youngest, there was an older boy, Uncle }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 Will}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 , there's Uncle Fred, Aunt Nell, Aunt Min, mum and Daisy. So there's six of them. So there was four before that 
so they must have has some years living in their house with the ground at the side of Southwark Park. Yes. Hadn't thought about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Were you brought up to feel that it was possible to move from one social class to another or that you were in a certa
in station of life and that's where you stayed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No, we were all - we were all too }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13985300\charrsid3306671 busy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671  to think about it I think. Or in my time, I don't know about the younger lot. The younger half a dozen. But me with us five older ones, we were just always wor
king and - and we got on with it. We only worked - lived as a team. You know, any trouble - that we would all knuckle down and - and look after this, that - or any of the babies ill, we would all - rustle round, I can only say that. We were the family and
 we - we kept as the family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 There weren't any people you knew who started off as working class and became shop-keepers for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. No. Not at - not among our friends. 'Cos there are - they - there are a lot of these - us grandchildren - a
ll the grandchildren are all - high and mighty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 But that's more recent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes, 'cos that - and they're younger anyway. But all the grandchildren have all done well for themselves. One is - is - well I don't know whether you call it well for himsel
f but - he was at university and - he's got his flat in London, he doesn't go home, no, and - Richard has got a flat in London. Flat - not in London - but of course he is studying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you remember anyone at that time being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Yes. My mother's friend over the road. As - as she used to call her, Mrs Dedman. Oh she's a real lady. And then I had a friend the same. And - we used to say - they - they really are - gentleman, of this man, Mr Chalice and that - a
nd - he really is a gentleman. Which they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Why do you think that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Well he was a professor of singing. Yes, and that - they - they were - but they didn't mind making friends of us who were - I wouldn't say on the breadline but we were poor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Where was this friend of yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh - at home. Before I married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Who was Mrs Dedman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Well she was the friend over the road who lived opposite in Anchor Street. But mother knew her when she lived in the Jamaica Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Why do you think she felt this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
I don't know, she - probably because her two daughters were - nurses. Might have been. But - she was a nice woman. Very nice woman. Upright with a - a - you know, a big bust, that type, stood there like that. Isn't it strange. T
hey used to in those days. Yes, that's right, yes. Probably, Mrs Dedman was. And - of course the teachers she was very fond of, my teachers, 'cos they did used to come. And she used to go to school with another one, another one with a presence. Mrs Channi
n
g. And - when I said about Mrs Channing was taking us for singing and dancing, and - she said, Mrs F. Channing? So I - or Miss Channing - Mrs - mum used to go to school with her. So they were the same age evidently. She - she used to like her. She said, o
h yes, I used to like her. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 And Miss Pegram, my own form teacher, she liked her because she used to come and visit her when she kept me away. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes. Yes. Yes. I'd like to meet them you know. Of course I expect they're all gone now, as I was only little.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 This was very interesting that she'd kept this friend from her own school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you know what sort of school she went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 No. Not mum. No I don't know. I don't know what they went to. Couldn't have been much for her to go to the tinsmiths firm, a factory.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Do you remember seeing a policeman around at all when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
Oh on the horses. Oh yes, 'cos in London - yes. What did we used to call them? We used to call them something, we had a name for them. I can't tell you, 
but the mounted police. Yes, we used to have a lot of them, I - I don't know whether they used to patrol the docks or not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 If you were naughty your mother never used to say, I'll call the policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Oh no. No. And I don't think - my mother never
 grumbled at us. Seldom. She didn't grumble at us, but she would make us keep quiet when dad was there, you know. Yes. Well to us. Not to - not to hurt us but - keep quiet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You just remember seeing the policeman on a horse do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Not coming round on foot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. No, I don't think we had any did we. We used to have all these - muffin men. And the lavender girls. Yes. Yes, calling, yes. Ringing his bell with his tray on his head. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Lavender girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Lavender, yes. She used
 to have a basket and she used to be outside the Colleen Ball - the pub - where the horse bus started from, and - she would be there - probably day time, 'cos it was the end of the market, at the end and she would be at the end. And - then I think when th
e
 market closed - the stalls went - no, they; couldn't have gone away, not 'til late. She used to come round during the afternoon then. Because the - the market - well Saturday night market was late. I only know - we used to shop Saturdays, for the - for t
he real market with the stalls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Anyone else who called round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No. I don't remember. Only the cats meat. But - the cats meat woman, put them under the knockers. She used to have a trail of cats behind her. Yes. They used to follow her. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 Cat's meat woman. }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Ha'penny. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4871271\charrsid3306671 
Ha'porth of cats' meat put on the skewer, under the knocker, and - used to go and get it then because - that could be jumped at by the cats, 'cos the houses were on the pavement like this, like these at Brightlingsea. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 And - or our houses w
ere - and - we'd see her going up the road still putting them up under the knockers and there'd be this trail of cats behind her. I couldn't have done that, I should have had to thrown them something. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 You said the house was a rented one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14100231 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 Did you ever see the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7043539 LC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11500731\charrsid3306671 
No, it was a landlady. And when we wanted something done - there was only me - now which house - no, there couldn't have been only me, we must have just moved into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Southwark
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Anchor Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} because - s
